A DAG-Inspired Word-Semantics Tokenizer and High Fidelity Semantic Parser for Ancient Greek
M1. Proposal:
We implement the framework as a layered semantic compiler. Each input passes through phonemic normalization, morphemic segmentation, lexeme normalization, semantic token assignment, syntactic/logical relation inference, and final DAG composition. All intermediate layers are serialized as structured JSON outputs, which allows us to evaluate stability and correctness at each stage rather than only at the final output layer. We run both single-item and batch analysis pipelines, and measure phonemic consistency, morphemic accuracy, lemma normalization accuracy, semantic token correctness, relation accuracy, and DAG validity.

The current method builds linguistic structure from the bottom up: phonemes are normalized first, then grouped into morphemes, then mapped to lexemes, then retyped as semantic tokens, then organized into syntactic/logical relations, then segmented into semantic blocks using an axiomatic boundary model rather than punctuation, and finally compiled into a typed DAG. The resulting system is interpretable, modular, and suitable for custom semantic analysis without relying on standard punctuation-based segmentation or purely frequency-driven tokenization.

S1. Abstract Ideas (Ἀφηρημέναι Ἰδέαι): 
Project overflow
This project does not begin by training a large end-to-end model over a mixed corpus.
Instead, it builds a runnable semantic compiler prototype whose workflow is:
text input → layered analysis → structured intermediate representations → DAG assembly → rule-based validation → statistical analysis
The guiding principle is that every layer must remain visible, inspectable, comparable, and scoreable.
The system therefore replaces frequency-driven tokenization with a word-semantics tokenizer based on linguistically meaningful units.

S2. Research Goals:
The goal is to construct a structured pipeline for Latin and Ancient Greek/Ελληνικά that preserves semantic stability by analyzing language through interpretable layers rather than opaque token statistics.

M2. Split Determinators:
Word split by phonetics and morpheme 
Word Analysis: What “Analysis” Means in This Project
Analysis here is not model loss minimization.
It is a layer-by-layer diagnosis.

