Open Greek and Latin Project
Logeion Greek Backends
logeion/logeion-backend: Backend scripts, files, etc. for parsing/updating dictionaries.


Sorted by priority (open to data-scrap):
1.  Direct Use: CTSAncientGreekXML
    This is best suited as the input layer for tokenization, as it has already undergone word segmentation and sentence splitting, and is available as a release/ZIP archive.
gcelano/CTSAncientGreekXML: This repository contains CTSized Ancient Greek Literature texts
Tokenized and sentence-split CTSized Ancient Greek texts (v1.1.0)
2.  Advanced Use: POStaggedAncientGreekXML / LemmatizedAncientGreekXML
    If you require more than just tokens—specifically, if you also want to readily access Part-of-Speech (POS) tags or lemmas—these two options offer greater convenience:
    •   `POStaggedAncientGreekXML` = Tokenized + Sentence-split + POS-tagged.
gcelano/POStaggedAncientGreekXML: This repository contains Ancient Greek texts after tokenization, sentence split, and POS-tagging
    •   `LemmatizedAncientGreekXML` = Tokenized + POS-tagged + Sentence-split + Lemmatized.
3. Not Recommended for Direct Use as "Ready-made CSVs": First1KGreek / Perseus Canonical
These two resources are, in themselves, repositories of raw TEI/XML texts; they are neither ready-made CSV files nor pre-processed token tables. First1KGreek is explicitly an XML file repository, while Perseus Canonical serves as a repository of canonical TEI XML texts.
gcelano/LemmatizedAncientGreekXML

B-Tree Structural Generation:
B-Tree Structural Generation provides the ordered realization layer of the project. After semantic analysis and DAG validation, semantic units are reorganized into a bounded hierarchical tree that supports phrase-, clause-, sentence-, and section-level generation. This structure preserves compositional relations and logical scope while preventing uncontrolled linear drift. In this framework, the DAG functions as the semantic truth structure, while the B-Tree functions as the ordered generation scaffold.
1. Purpose
B-Tree Structural Generation is the project’s hierarchical realization layer.
Its role is to organize semantic material into a stable branching structure before final text realization. Instead of generating a passage as a flat token stream, the system generates it through a balanced semantic tree whose nodes preserve order, scope, and compositional relations.
The B-Tree is not used as a database index here in the narrow systems sense; it is used as a structural generation model inspired by bounded branching and ordered insertion. Its main advantage is that it prevents uncontrolled drift by forcing generated material to enter the output through validated local branches.

2. Core Idea
The pipeline becomes:
phoneme
→ morpheme
→ lexeme
→ semantic token
→ syntax / logic relations
→ DAG
→ B-Tree structural organization
→ linearized passage
The DAG stores full typed relations.
The B-Tree provides a generation-time ordered hierarchy for assembling larger spans.
So the division of labor is:
DAG = semantic truth structure


B-Tree = ordered generation structure



3. Why a B-Tree Structure
A B-Tree-like structure is useful because it gives:
bounded branching


stable insertion order


efficient regrouping of units


better control over large-section generation


reduced risk of one bad local continuation corrupting the whole passage


Instead of generating sentence material linearly from left to right, the system first groups units into semantic blocks, then inserts them into a bounded branching tree.

4. Generation Units
The leaves of the B-Tree are not raw characters.
They are validated semantic units such as:
morpheme bundles


lexemes


semantic tokens


predicate-argument clusters


logical-scope blocks


discourse blocks


So a generation leaf may be:
u_i = (\text{lexeme}, \text{semantic type}, \text{role}, \text{constraints})
Example leaf:
μεγαλόδους


semantic type = ENTITY


internal morphemes = μεγαλο- | οδους


allowed attachments = ATTRIBUTE, PREDICATE, GROUNDS_TO



5. Tree Levels
The B-Tree can be built in layers.
Level 1: lexical leaves
Leaves hold validated lexical-semantic units.
Level 2: phrase clusters
Leaves are grouped into small phrase-level units:
entity phrase


predicate phrase


attribute phrase


operator phrase


Level 3: clause branches
Phrase clusters are grouped into clause-level branches.
Level 4: sentence branches
Clauses are grouped into sentence-level branches.
Level 5: section branches
Sentences are grouped into passage-level or discourse-level branches.
So the hierarchy is:
SECTION
  ├── SENTENCE
  │     ├── CLAUSE
  │     │     ├── PHRASE
  │     │     │     └── LEXICAL UNIT

6. Node Types
A practical B-Tree generation schema may use these node types:
SECTION_NODE


SENTENCE_NODE


CLAUSE_NODE


PHRASE_NODE


LEXEME_NODE


MORPHEME_NODE


OPERATOR_NODE


Each node stores:
content label


child order


semantic constraints


agreement features


scope compatibility


confidence



7. Insertion Rules
Generation is performed by constrained insertion.
A semantic unit may only be inserted if:
its parent node allows that semantic type,


its attachment does not violate scope,


agreement constraints are satisfied,


the local branch stays structurally legal,


the resulting tree remains ordered and balanced enough for realization.


This makes the B-Tree a constraint-preserving generation scaffold.

8. Relation to DAG
The B-Tree is derived from the DAG, not independent from it.
DAG → B-Tree conversion
extract semantic nodes from the DAG


cluster them by local relation:


modifier groups


predicate-argument groups


operator-scope groups


assign cluster types


insert clusters into hierarchical B-Tree levels


preserve ordering constraints from the source or target realization


So the DAG is the deep representation, and the B-Tree is the realizable ordered projection.

9. Example with 
μεγαλόδους
Suppose the DAG contains:
LEXEME(μεγαλόδους)


MORPHEME(μεγαλο-)


MORPHEME(οδους)


SEMANTIC_ROLE(ENTITY)


Then the B-Tree realization may look like:
PHRASE_NODE: ENTITY_PHRASE
   └── LEXEME_NODE: μεγαλόδους
         ├── MORPHEME_NODE: μεγαλο-
         └── MORPHEME_NODE: οδους
If used inside a sentence:
SENTENCE_NODE
  ├── PHRASE_NODE: ENTITY_PHRASE
  │      └── μεγαλόδους
  └── PHRASE_NODE: PREDICATE_PHRASE
         └── ...
If extended to a larger section, the entity can recur as a tracked branch across multiple sentences.

10. Generation Procedure
A simple B-Tree Structural Generation algorithm can be defined as:
Step 1
Take validated DAG nodes.
Step 2
Group them into local semantic clusters.
Step 3
Create leaf nodes from lexical units.
Step 4
Merge leaves into bounded phrase nodes.
Step 5
Merge phrase nodes into clause nodes.
Step 6
Merge clause nodes into sentence nodes.
Step 7
Linearize the tree into surface text.
This gives:
\text{DAG} \rightarrow \text{B-Tree} \rightarrow \text{Surface Passage}

11. Advantages
This structure gives the project several benefits:
local errors remain local


scope is easier to preserve


section-level generation becomes manageable


semantic blocks can be reordered without destroying the whole structure


generation is more interpretable than left-to-right unconstrained continuation


It is especially suitable for your project because you want:
compositional stability


explicit semantic control


low drift in small-data settings


compatibility with DAG validation



12. Minimal Formal Definition
Let D be the validated semantic DAG.
Let T be the B-Tree generation structure derived from D.
Then generation proceeds by a mapping:
\Phi: D \rightarrow T
where T satisfies:
ordered hierarchy


bounded branching


semantic type compatibility


scope preservation


realizability into linear text


Then the surface realization function is:
R(T) = \text{generated passage}
So the full generation model is:
R(\Phi(D))

MUC-Semantics Accuracy Check:
We check the F-measure, precision and recall of the following as well as the beta customized balance of the F-score: F_β = [(1 + β^2) P R] / [(β^2 P) + R], Precision = TP / (TP + FP), Recall = TP / (TP + FN)
We evaluate semantic accuracy using precision, recall, and F1 over gold and predicted semantic units. A semantic unit may be a morpheme analysis, a normalized lexeme, a semantic token label, or a typed DAG relation. Precision is defined as the proportion of predicted units that are correct, recall as the proportion of gold units recovered by the system, and F1 as their harmonic mean. We report both layer-specific scores and an overall weighted MUC-Semantics F1.
We evaluate the system with precision, recall, and F-measure (F1) at five distinct levels.
At each level, let:
G = gold-standard units


P = predicted units


M = correctly matched units


Then:
\text{Precision} = \frac{|M|}{|P|}
\text{Recall} = \frac{|M|}{|G|}
F_1 = \frac{2 \cdot \text{Precision} \cdot \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision} + \text{Recall}}
Each level defines its own semantic unit and matching rule.

Accuracy of Parsing
This level evaluates whether the system correctly recovers the formal structure of the input.
Unit of evaluation
A parsing unit may be:
a constituent,


a dependency relation,


a morpheme boundary,


a phrase boundary,


or a typed syntactic edge in the DAG.


Gold vs prediction
Gold: the correct parse structure


Prediction: the parse produced by the system


Precision
How many predicted structural relations are correct.
\text{Precision}_{\text{parse}} = \frac{|\text{correct parse relations}|}{|\text{predicted parse relations}|}
Recall
How many gold structural relations were recovered.
\text{Recall}_{\text{parse}} = \frac{|\text{correct parse relations}|}{|\text{gold parse relations}|}
F1
F1_{\text{parse}} = \frac{2 \cdot P_{\text{parse}} \cdot R_{\text{parse}}}{P_{\text{parse}} + R_{\text{parse}}}
Example
If the gold parse contains 10 correct constituent or dependency relations, and the system predicts 9, of which 7 are correct:
P_{\text{parse}} = \frac{7}{9} \qquad R_{\text{parse}} = \frac{7}{10}
Accuracy of Interpretation
This level evaluates whether the system correctly assigns meaning after parsing.
Unit of evaluation
An interpretation unit may be:
a semantic token label,


a semantic role,


a logical operator scope,


a coreference link,


a lexeme-to-semantic mapping,


or a typed semantic edge in the DAG.


Gold vs prediction
Gold: the intended semantic interpretation


Prediction: the semantic representation inferred by the system


Precision
How many predicted meanings are correct.
\text{Precision}_{\text{interp}} = \frac{|\text{correct semantic units}|}{|\text{predicted semantic units}|}
Recall
How many gold semantic units were recovered.
\text{Recall}_{\text{interp}} = \frac{|\text{correct semantic units}|}{|\text{gold semantic units}|}
F1
F1_{\text{interp}} = \frac{2 \cdot P_{\text{interp}} \cdot R_{\text{interp}}}{P_{\text{interp}} + R_{\text{interp}}}
Example
If the system correctly identifies:
μεγαλο- as a size intensifier,


οδους as tooth,


but assigns the whole lexeme the wrong semantic role,


then the interpretation score reflects partial semantic success rather than complete failure.

Accuracy of Data Collecting and Transforming
This level evaluates the correctness of the input data pipeline.
It checks whether the system correctly collects, normalizes, and transforms source material before analysis.
Unit of evaluation
A data-transform unit may be:
a correctly extracted token,


a correctly aligned passage,


a correctly preserved token order,


a correctly normalized orthographic form,


a correctly transformed XML field into CSV/JSON,


or a correctly linked metadata field.


Gold vs prediction
Gold: manually verified or reference-transformed data


Prediction: the output of the collection/transformation pipeline


Precision
How many transformed items are correct.
\text{Precision}_{\text{data}} = \frac{|\text{correct transformed units}|}{|\text{transformed units produced}|}
Recall
How many required gold units were preserved or recovered.
\text{Recall}_{\text{data}} = \frac{|\text{correct transformed units}|}{|\text{gold units expected}|}
F1
F1_{\text{data}} = \frac{2 \cdot P_{\text{data}} \cdot R_{\text{data}}}{P_{\text{data}} + R_{\text{data}}}
Example
If an XML source contains 100 tokens and the transformation pipeline outputs 98 tokens, of which 95 are correctly preserved and aligned:
P_{\text{data}} = \frac{95}{98} \qquad R_{\text{data}} = \frac{95}{100}
This layer is especially important because a semantic system built on corrupted input will fail even if later modules are well designed.

Accuracy of Transcribing and Translating a Passage
This level measures whether a source passage is correctly rendered into another orthographic or linguistic form.
It covers:
transcription,


transliteration,


translation,


and structured passage transfer into the semantic layer.


Unit of evaluation
A unit may be:
a phoneme correspondence,


a syllable correspondence,


a token-level transliteration,


a lemma-level translation,


a clause-level translation,


or a semantic equivalence unit.


Gold vs prediction
Gold: verified transcription/translation


Prediction: the system’s transcription/translation output


Precision
How many produced transcribed/translated units are correct.
\text{Precision}_{\text{trans}} = \frac{|\text{correct transcribed or translated units}|}{|\text{produced units}|}
Recall
How many gold units were successfully captured.
\text{Recall}_{\text{trans}} = \frac{|\text{correct transcribed or translated units}|}{|\text{gold units}|}
F1
F1_{\text{trans}} = \frac{2 \cdot P_{\text{trans}} \cdot R_{\text{trans}}}{P_{\text{trans}} + R_{\text{trans}}}
Example
For a passage containing a technical word like μεγαλόδους:
transcription accuracy checks whether the phonological/orthographic mapping is correct,


translation accuracy checks whether the semantic content “large-tooth” is preserved,


and semantic translation accuracy checks whether the translated passage retains the correct semantic roles and relations.
Accuracy of Generating a Passage
This level evaluates whether the system can generate a passage that is structurally and semantically correct.
Unit of evaluation
A generation unit may be:
a generated token,


a generated morpheme sequence,


a generated semantic relation,


a generated clause,


or a generated passage-level semantic structure.


Gold vs prediction
Gold: target passage or accepted semantic structure


Prediction: system-generated output


Precision
How many generated units are correct and appropriate.
\text{Precision}_{\text{gen}} = \frac{|\text{correct generated units}|}{|\text{generated units}|}
Recall
How much of the gold target content was generated.
\text{Recall}_{\text{gen}} = \frac{|\text{correct generated units}|}{|\text{gold target units}|}
F1
F1_{\text{gen}} = \frac{2 \cdot P_{\text{gen}} \cdot R_{\text{gen}}}{P_{\text{gen}} + R_{\text{gen}}}
Interpretation
high precision means generation is restrained and not full of hallucinated content,


high recall means the generated passage captures the intended content fully,


high F1 means the system is both accurate and complete.

Global MUC-Semantics Accuracy
If you want one overall score, define:
\text{MUC-Semantics-F1}=w_1F1_{\text{parse}}+w_2F1_{\text{interp}}+w_3F1_{\text{data}}+
w_4F1_{\text{trans}}+w_5F1_{\text{gen}}
with
w_1+w_2+w_3+w_4+w_5=1
A reasonable weighting for your project might be:
w_1=0.20,\quad
w_2=0.25,\quad
w_3=0.15,\quad
w_4=0.20,\quad
w_5=0.20
This gives slightly higher importance to interpretation, since your framework is fundamentally semantic rather than merely formal.

M7. CSV and DAG Exports: 
Exports to files written on the local disk
M7.1 Unified token CSV
Recommended fields:
text_cts, passage, token_id, token_form, join, editorial_tag, sentence_id, pos, lemma, source_repo
M7.2 Merged token table
After custom morphology and lexeme overrides, add:
token_uid, normalized_form, morpheme_split, morph_analysis, pos_custom, lemma_custom, confidence, pos_final, lemma_final
M7.3 DAG export
Generate:
	•	nodes.csv
	•	edges.csv
Current DAG schema:
Nodes
	•	TEXT
	•	SENTENCE
	•	TOKEN
	•	MORPHEME
	•	LEXEME
	•	SEMANTIC_ROLE
	•	MORPH_ANALYSIS
Edges
	•	HAS_SENTENCE
	•	HAS_TOKEN
	•	HAS_MORPHEME
	•	REALIZES_LEXEME
	•	HAS_SEMANTIC_ROLE
	•	HAS_MORPH_ANALYSIS


T1. Single and Multiple Cell Runners:
A single-item script may analyze the example word directly:
import json
from src.pipeline import SemanticCompiler
resources = {}
compiler = SemanticCompiler(resources)
text = "μεγαλόδους"
lang = "ancient_greek"
result = compiler.analyze(text, lang)
print(json.dumps(result.__dict__, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))
Command:
python scripts/run_single.py
This verifies that the entire pipeline works end to end.
A multiple-item script may analyze the entire direct sentence of a passage or a quote:

T2. Mass Generation Runners:
We use three execution scales: a single-item runner for end-to-end validation on one token or phrase, a multiple-item runner for controlled batch analysis on sentences or quoted segments, and a mass generation runner for large-scale corpus processing. The mass runner loads structured input cells, applies the semantic compiler to each cell, serializes intermediate and final outputs, and exports token tables, graph tables, and evaluation logs for downstream analysis.
T2.1 Definition
A Mass Generation Runner is a scalable execution layer that:
loads large batches of source texts


splits them into processing cells


applies the semantic compiler to each cell


serializes all intermediate and final outputs


supports resumable, inspectable, and reproducible runs
T2.2 Processing Unit
A mass runner may define its processing cell as one of the following:
token


lexical item


phrase


sentence


line


passage


quotation block


full document segment


The processing unit should be configurable depending on the experiment.
T2.3 Standard Workflow
source corpus
  ↓
dataset loader
  ↓
cell splitter
  ↓
SemanticCompiler.analyze(cell)
  ↓
structured output writer
  ↓
metrics / logs / graph export
T2.4 Minimal Mass Runner Structure
import json
from pathlib import Path
from src.pipeline import SemanticCompiler

resources = {}
compiler = SemanticCompiler(resources)

input_path = Path("data/corpus/passages.jsonl")
output_path = Path("outputs/mass_results.jsonl")

with input_path.open("r", encoding="utf-8") as fin, output_path.open("w", encoding="utf-8") as fout:
    for line in fin:
        item = json.loads(line)
        result = compiler.analyze(item["text"], item["language"])
        fout.write(json.dumps(result.__dict__, ensure_ascii=False) + "\n")

Command:
python scripts/run_mass.py

T2.5 Required Components
A Mass Generation Runner should include:
Loader
Reads:
JSONL


CSV


XML-derived tables


tokenized passage files


Splitter
Splits input into units such as:
single sentence


quoted segment


semantic block


passage window


Runner
Calls:
compiler.analyze(text, language)
for each processing cell.
Writer
Stores:
raw structured outputs


merged token tables


nodes.csv


edges.csv


evaluation logs


Logger
Tracks:
item id


status


runtime


failure reason


graph validity


output path
T2.6 Output Products
A mass runner should produce one or more of the following:
mass_results.jsonl


merged_tokens.csv


nodes.csv


edges.csv


evaluation_summary.json


error_log.jsonl
T2.7 Use Cases
Mass Generation Runners are used for:
full-corpus semantic compilation


large-scale tokenization experiments


morphology and lexeme normalization at corpus level


DAG construction over many passages


comparative runs across languages


later multimodal grounding experiments
T2.8 Recommended Modes
Mode A: Clean Tokenization Mode
Input:
CTSAncientGreekXML-derived cells


Output:
token-level results without inherited POS/lemma bias


Mode B: Lemmatized Baseline Mode
Input:
LemmatizedAncientGreekXML-derived cells


Output:
token + morphology + lexeme baseline


Mode C: Custom Semantic Mode
Input:
merged token tables with custom morphology and lexeme layers


Output:
full semantic token and DAG structures



T2.9 Practical Goals
The purpose of a mass runner is not merely speed.
Its purpose is to make large-scale semantic analysis:
reproducible


inspectable


modular


resumable


evaluation-ready



M8. Best Practical Startovers
The implementation should not begin with the full system all at once.
Step 1: Word-level pipeline
	•	phoneme
	•	morpheme
	•	lexeme
	•	semantic token
Step 2: Phrase-level relations
	•	modifier
	•	compound
	•	transliteration relation
Step 3: Syntax / logic
	•	negation
	•	comparison
	•	condition
Step 4: Grounding
	•	evidence nodes
	•	GROUNDS_TO edges


M9. Comparison and Generation of Large-Section Texts:
M9 extends the framework to the comparison and generation of large textual sections, including multi-sentence passages and quoted blocks. Rather than relying on linear continuation, the system composes section-level outputs from validated semantic blocks and sentence DAGs, then evaluates them through section-level structural and semantic precision, recall, and F1. This allows paragraph-scale comparison, controlled passage generation, and discourse-level graph analysis while preserving interpretability and validation at every layer.
M9 extends the system from token-level and sentence-level analysis to the comparison, reconstruction, and controlled generation of large textual sections, such as paragraphs, continuous passages, quoted blocks, or aligned multi-sentence units. The purpose of this module is not to generate fluent text by unconstrained continuation, but to produce and compare larger passages through the accumulation of validated lower-level structures.
M9.1 Goal
The goal of this module is to make large-section processing possible while preserving:
semantic continuity,


structural traceability,


logical scope consistency,


lexeme normalization consistency,


and DAG-level validity across multiple sentences.


This module therefore serves two complementary purposes:
Comparison of large textual sections

 It compares two or more passages at the level of:


token structure,


morpheme structure,


lexeme normalization,


semantic roles,


logical operators,


and graph topology.


Generation of large textual sections

 It generates multi-sentence output from validated semantic graphs rather than from raw linear token continuation.


M9.2 Input Units
A large textual section may be defined as:
a paragraph,


a quoted block,


a passage window,


a sequence of adjacent sentences,


or a discourse segment extracted from a source text.


Each large section is treated as an ordered sequence of smaller analysis cells:
S = (c_1, c_2, \dots, c_n)
where each cell c_i may be a sentence, clause block, or semantic block.
M9.3 Comparison of Large Sections
M9.3.1 Purpose
Large-section comparison checks whether two passages preserve the same structure and meaning, even when:
word order differs,


lexical choices differ,


morphology differs,


or translation/transcription introduces surface variation.


M9.3.2 Comparison layers
Comparison is performed at several levels:
Token sequence comparison

 Are the token units aligned and preserved?


Morpheme sequence comparison

 Do the passages preserve the same internal morphological structure?


Lexeme comparison

 Do they normalize to the same lexical core?


Semantic role comparison

 Do the same entities, attributes, predicates, and operators appear?


Logical structure comparison

 Are negation, comparison, condition, and scope preserved?


DAG comparison

 Are the two semantic graphs topologically and semantically equivalent or near-equivalent?


M9.3.3 Output
The system outputs:
local alignment tables,


block-level similarity scores,


graph overlap scores,


and a global passage comparison score.


Example output schema:
{
  "section_id_a": "passage_A",
  "section_id_b": "passage_B",
  "token_similarity": 0.84,
  "morpheme_similarity": 0.79,
  "lexeme_similarity": 0.88,
  "semantic_similarity": 0.81,
  "graph_similarity": 0.76,
  "differences": [
    {"type": "operator_scope_shift", "location": "sentence_3"},
    {"type": "entity_role_change", "location": "sentence_5"}
  ]
}
M9.4 Generation of Large Sections
M9.4.1 Principle
Large-section generation is not performed by next-token continuation alone.
Instead, generation proceeds from:
validated lower-level units,


validated semantic blocks,


validated sentence graphs,


and finally a section-level graph.


Thus the generation path is:
semantic blocks
  ↓
sentence DAGs
  ↓
section-level DAG
  ↓
ordered realization
  ↓
generated passage
M9.4.2 Generation stages
Select semantic units

 Choose the entities, predicates, attributes, and operators to be expressed.


Assemble sentence-level subgraphs

 Group semantic material into coherent sentence structures.


Assemble discourse-level graph

 Link sentence graphs through continuity, reference, and logical progression.


Linearize

 Convert the graph into ordered lexical realizations.


Surface realization

 Produce the final large-section text.


M9.4.3 Constraint
At each stage, the system must preserve:
attachment legality,


scope closure,


graph acyclicity,


and discourse continuity.


No sentence may be added if it breaks graph validity.
M9.5 Section-Level DAG
To support large-section analysis, the DAG is expanded from token- and sentence-level nodes to section-level nodes.
Additional node types
SECTION


BLOCK


DISCOURSE_ROLE


REFERENCE_CHAIN


Additional edge types
HAS_BLOCK


PRECEDES


CONTINUES_TOPIC


REFERS_BACK_TO


SCOPES_OVER_SECTION


CONTRASTS_WITH


SUPPORTS


This allows the project to represent not only local syntax, but also paragraph-scale discourse organization.
M9.6 Accuracy Check for Large Sections
Large-section comparison and generation should be evaluated using the same semantic precision / recall / F1 framework, extended to section-level units.
Units of comparison
A section-level evaluation unit may be:
a semantic block,


a sentence subgraph,


a discourse relation,


a reference chain,


or a complete section-level DAG edge.


Metrics
For section-level comparison:
\text{Precision}_{\text{section}} = \frac{|\text{correct predicted section units}|}{|\text{predicted section units}|}
\text{Recall}_{\text{section}} = \frac{|\text{correct predicted section units}|}{|\text{gold section units}|}
F1_{\text{section}} = \frac{2 \cdot P_{\text{section}} \cdot R_{\text{section}}}{P_{\text{section}} + R_{\text{section}}}
These scores can be computed separately for:
structural continuity,


reference continuity,


logical continuity,


and full graph realization.



M9.7 Practical Execution Modes
Mode A: Comparison Mode
Input:
two aligned passages or large sections


Output:
similarity scores,


mismatched units,


and graph-level differences


Mode B: Reconstruction Mode
Input:
gold semantic graph for a section


Output:
reconstructed text from graph realization


Mode C: Controlled Generation Mode
Input:
selected semantic blocks and discourse ordering constraints


Output:
generated large-section passage with validation logs


M9.8 Mass Runner Integration
This module is designed to work directly with the Mass Generation Runners.
A mass runner may process:
entire passages,


multiple paragraphs,


chapter-level samples,


or aligned bilingual / multilingual sections.


Pipeline:
large-section source
  ↓
cell splitter
  ↓
sentence/block analysis
  ↓
section DAG builder
  ↓
comparison or generation
  ↓
evaluation and export
Outputs may include:
section_results.jsonl


section_nodes.csv


section_edges.csv


section_comparison.json


section_generation.json


section_eval_summary.json



M9.9 Example with a Multi-Sentence Section
Suppose a section contains:
a sentence introducing a taxon,


a sentence describing its morphology,


a sentence making a comparative claim.


The system should:
preserve the taxon as the same entity across sentences,


preserve attribute inheritance,


preserve comparison scope,


and maintain discourse continuity in the section-level graph.


Thus, if μεγαλόδους appears in sentence 1 and is elaborated in sentences 2–3, the system must track it as a continuous semantic object rather than treating each occurrence independently.

